		<h2>What is it?</h2>

		<p>Ockley is a simple web-based editor for Force.com Apex and Visualforce.
		    It aspires to be the textpad/notepad of Force.com development tools.
		</p>
		<p>Here it is with the Redmond theme:<p>
		<a href="images/ockley_lg.png">
			<img id="ockley_img" src="images/ockley_sm.png" width="682px" height="414px" alt="a small pic of ockley in action">
		</a>
		
		        
		<h2>Why do I care?</h2>
		<p>
		    Maybe you do and maybe you don't.
		
		    <ul>
		        <li>Do you work on the 
		        	<a href="http://www.salesforce.com/platform/" alt="Force.com platform">Force.com platform</a>?
		        </li>
		        <li>Are you interested in alternatives to the Eclipse based 
		        	<a href="http://wiki.developerforce.com/index.php/Force.com_IDE" alt="Force.com IDE">Force.com IDE</a>?
		        </li>
		        <li>Ockley is open-source. You can 
		        	<a href="https://github.com/mattpage/Ockley" alt="github link">change it</a> if you want to!
		        </li>
		    </ul>
		
		</p>
		<br />
		<h2>What else?</h2>
		<p>Ockley is built on 
			<a href="http://nodejs.org">node.js</a> and the 
			<a href="http://expressjs.com/">express</a> framework.
		</p>
		<p>The front-end is a 
			<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Layer_cake">layer cake</a>
		    of <a href="http://html5boilerplate.com/">HTML5 Boilerplate</a>, 
		    <a href="http://jquery.com">jQuery</a>, and <a href="http://jqueryui.com/">jQueryUI</a>.
		</p>
		<p>
		    The editor is <a href="http://codemirror.net/">CodeMirror</a> with plugins for 
		    <a href="http://www.salesforce.com/us/developer/docs/apexcode/index.htm">Apex</a> and what-not.
		    The sexy forms are thanks to <a href="http://thrivingkings.com/formly/">Formly</a>.
		</p>
		<p>
		    Special thanks to <a href="http://www.famfamfam.com/lab/icons/silk/">Mark James</a> for the awesome icons!
		</p>
		<p>
		    Special thanks to <a href="https://github.com/joshbirk">Josh Birk</a> for the OAuth help!
		</p>
